    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-03-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-03-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="77"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d77">
                <head>77. Telegram 41598 From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to
                    the <gloss type="to">Mission in Geneva</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d77fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1967–1969, DEF 18–3.
                        Confidential; Immediate. It was repeated to USNATO, <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                            >USUN</gloss>, all <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> capitals,
                        Tokyo, and Moscow. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_KRH2">Kranich</persName>
                            (<gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>/IR) and Scoville (<gloss
                            target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>/ST); cleared in <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss>, J/<gloss target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss>, and
                        the White House; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                            >Rogers</persName>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d77fn2">Secretary of State <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> cabled detailed instructions to Arms
                        Control and Disarmament Agency Director Smith during the <gloss
                            target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss> conference. <persName corresp="#p_RWP1"
                            >Rogers</persName> confirmed that the U.S. supported a <gloss
                            target="#t_CTB1">CTB</gloss> providing the on-site inspections were
                        sufficiently verified and to restrict production of fissionable weapons
                        materials. Moreover, the U.S. favored a seabed arms treaty, providing a list
                        of four questions were satisfactorily discussed.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1969-03-18"
                        >March 18, 1969</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>FOR SMITH FROM THE SECRETARY</p>
                <p>You are instructed to take the following positions in the <gloss
                        target="#t_ENDC1">ENDC</gloss>:</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="underline">Comprehensive Test Ban (<gloss target="#t_CTB1"
                                >CTB</gloss>).</hi> You will indicate that <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >US</gloss> supports conclusion of a Comprehensive Test Ban adequately
                        verified (on site inspection). You should also make clear that the <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss> will assist in any reasonable effort to
                        achieve greater understanding of the verification issue involved, and in
                        this connection you are instructed to reiterate the <gloss target="#t_US1"
                            >US</gloss> seismic investigation proposal of December 5, 1968.</item>
                    <pb facs="d77-02" n="2" xml:id="d77-02"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="underline">Cut-Off of Fissionable Materials.</hi> You are
                        authorized to reiterate <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> support for a
                        cut-off in production of fissionable materials for weapons purposes. You
                        should propose modified verification procedure of cut-off through acceptance
                        by nuclear states of <gloss target="#t_IAEA1">IAEA</gloss> safeguards on
                        declared facilities. Your presentation should retain offer transfer agreed
                        amounts <gloss target="#t_U1">U</gloss>–235 and PU to peaceful purposes, but
                        should leave open question whether all material should come from
                        demonstrated destruction of nuclear weapons.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="underline">Arms Control of the Seabeds.</hi> You are authorized to
                        state that <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> favors a treaty which would ban
                        the emplacement or fixing of nuclear weapons or other weapons of mass
                        destruction on the seabed. To that end you should seek discussion of the
                        critical factors which need to be considered in developing such an
                        agreement. The list of critical factors to be discussed should include: <list>
                            <label>(a)</label>
                            <item>What weapons should be included within the terms “weapons of mass
                                destruction? Launching platforms and delivery <pb facs="d77-03"
                                    n="3" xml:id="d77-03"/> vehicles?”</item>
                            <label>(b)</label>
                            <item>What constitutes “emplace or fix” to the seabed?</item>
                            <label>(c)</label>
                            <item>What forms of verification are necessary for such an
                                agreement?</item>
                            <label>(d)</label>
                            <item>To what areas of the seabed should the prohibition of the
                                agreement apply?</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>You should not allow the prohibition to be extended to conventional weapons nor
                    to peaceful nuclear explosive devices. You should also make clear the <gloss
                        target="#t_US1">US</gloss> cannot accept complete demilitarization of the
                    seabed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
